The Wiborgs maintained homes in Cincinnati, New York City, and Long Island ("The Dunes"). The Wiborg family was involved in a number of social and civic organizations, and in his semi-retirement Frank Wiborg became engaged in politics. In 1907-1908 Wiborg served as secretary of the National Council of Commerce, a body created by and reporting to the Secretary of Commerce and Labor during the Theodore Roosevelt administration. President Taft appointed Wiborg Assistant Secretary of Commerce and Labor in 1909. Wiborg accompanied General Nelson Appleton Miles, who was married to one of Adeline Sherman's cousins, on several trips such as an excursion to the American Southwest in 1896 and a trip around the world in 1902 (Wiborg later used his diaries from this trip to produce 
                     The Travels of an Unofficial Attaché
                  ).
